equence, international tribunals and domestic bodies have recently made greater use of guilty pleas, many of which have been secured through plea bargaining. This book examines those guilty pleas and the methods used to obtain them, presenting analyses of practices in Sierra Leone, East Timor, Cambodia, Argentina, Bosnia, and Rwanda. Although current plea bargaining practices may be theoretically unsupportable and can give rise to severe victim dissatisfaction, the author argues that the practice is justified as a means of increasing the proportion of international offenders who can be prosecuted. She then incorporates principles drawn from the domestic practice of restorative justice to construct a model guilty plea system to be used for international crimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aDroit international pénal. 0aInternational crimes. 0aInternational criminal courtsxRules and practice. 0aNégociation de peine. 0aPlea bargaining. 0aTribunaux criminels internationauxxRèglements et procédure. 4aLaw -- Criminal Law. 4aLaw -- International and Comparative Law. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476799640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767996423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767996/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles